sex, England":"Horam, Sussex, England","Bosmere, Suffolk, England":"Bosmere, Suffolk, England","Somerleyton, Suffolk, England":"Somerleyton, Suffolk, England","Horham, Hartismere, Suffolk":"Hartismere, Suffolk, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Horham, Suffolk, England":"Horham, Suffolk, England","Suffolk":"Suffolk, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Stonham, Bosmere, Suffolk":"Earl Stonham, Suffolk, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1230–1272":"1230–1272","1230–1271":"1230–1271","1250–1299":"1250–1299","1257–Female":"1257–Deceased","1195–1239":"1195–1239","1239":"1239","1249":"1249","1257":"1257","1299":"1299","about 1257":"about 1257","1230":"1230","1250":"1250","1272":"1272","1195":"1195","1271":"1271","Horam, Sussex, England":"Horam, Sussex, England","Bosmere, Suffolk, England":"Bosmere, Suffolk, England","Somerleyton, Suffolk, England":"Somerleyton, Suffolk, England","Horham, Hartismere, Suffolk":"Hartismere, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","Horham, Suffolk, England":"Horham, Suffolk, England","Suffolk":"Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","Stonham, Bosmere, Suffolk":"Earl Stonham, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Jernigan","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Suffolk): of uncertain origin. Reaney believes it to be of Breton origin, probably identical with the Old Breton personal name <i>Iarnuuocon</i> ‘iron famous’, taken to East Anglia by Bretons at the time of the Norman Conquest. Compare   Journigan  .","History: Thomas Jernigan was granted land at Somerton, VA, in 1668. Many of his descendants were sea captains. His son, also called Thomas, settled on Martha's Vineyard, MA, in 1712."],"variants":[{"name":"Jarnigan","meanings":["English: variant of   Jernigan  ."]},{"name":"Jarnagin","meanings":["English: variant of   Jernigan  ."]},{"name":"Journigan","meanings":["Altered form of   Jernigan  ."]}]},{"name":"Hugh","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Hugues</i>, <i>Hugo</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>hug</i> ‘heart, mind, spirit’. It was originally a short form of various compound names containing this element. This was borne by the aristocracy of medieval France, adopted by the Normans, and introduced by them to Britain. It was consistently one of the most popular boys' names in the Middle Ages in England, but fell out of favour in the 16th century until it was revived in the 20th century. Little Hugh of Lincoln was a child supposed in the Middle Ages to have been murdered by Jews in about  1255 , a legend responsible for several outbursts of anti-Semitism at various times. The story is referred to by  Chaucer  in The Prioress's Tale. He is not to be confused with  St Hugh of Lincoln  (  1140–1200 ), bishop of Lincoln (  1186–1200 ), who was noted for his charity and good works, his piety, and his defence of the Church against the State. Since the later Middle Ages <i>Hugh</i> has also been used as an Anglicized form of the Gaelic name Aodh ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Hugh Jernigan of Horham was born in 1230, in Hartismere, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom as the son of Sir Hubert Jernegan. He married Ellen de Ingoldisthorpe in 1249, in Somerleyton, Suffolk, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. He died in 1272, in Earl Stonham, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 42."},"et":{"1230–1272":"1230–1272","1230–1271":"1230–1271","1250–1299":"1250–1299","1257–Female":"1257–Surnud","1195–1239":"1195–1239","1239":"1239","1249":"1249","1257":"1257","1299":"1299","about 1257":"umbes 1257","1230":"1230","1250":"1250","1272":"1272","1195":"1195","1271":"1271","Horam, Sussex, England":"Horam, Sussex, England","Bosmere, Suffolk, England":"Bosmere, Suffolk, England","Somerleyton, Suffolk, England":"Somerleyton, Suffolk, England","Horham, Hartismere, Suf